**who —** CHOANOFLAGELLATES — a life-science sphere — the brainless mind

**what —** A single cell with a whipping tail ringed by a collar — the humblest of microbes, and the closest living relative of every animal that has ever lived. In the choanoflagellate we see the doorstep we all crossed: the lone cell that, prompted by a bacterium, learns to gather into a colony. The threshold between one and many.

**where —** intelligence without a brain  Framework inputs: the living; the rule; the signal; the open question  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** A single cell with a whipping tail ringed by a collar — the humblest of microbes, and the closest living relative of every animal that has ever lived. In the choanoflagellate we see the doorstep we all crossed: the lone cell that, prompted by a bacterium, learns to gather into a colony. The threshold between one and many.

**how —** Crystallized from the public record of the science.

**◌ the mythos —** A single cell with a whipping tail ringed by a collar — the humblest of microbes, and the closest living relative of every animal that has ever lived. In the choanoflagellate we see the doorstep we all crossed: the lone cell that, prompted by a bacterium, learns to gather into a colony. The threshold between one and many. where a mind appears with no neurons in it

